Definition 3.12. A morphism of extensions of gerbes is a diagram $\UseTips\xymatrix@C=5ex@R=5ex{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}\ar[r]\ar[d]&\boldsymbol% {\mathcal{G}}\ar[r]^{F}\ar[d]_{D}&\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}\ar[d]_{E}\\ \boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}^{\prime}\ar[r]&\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}^{\prime}\ar[r% ]_{F^{\prime}}&\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}^{\prime}}$ of morphisms in $\operatorname{\boldsymbol{\operatorname{\mathsf{PreStGr}}}}X$, where the rows are extensions of gerbes, the square on the right is commutative up to $2$-isomorphism, and the square on the left is commutative. We denote this morphism of extensions by $(D,E)$.
Definition 6.1. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a sheaf of groups on $X$. (1) A normal filtration of $\mathcal{G}$ is a descending sequence $\{\mathcal{N}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ of sheaves of normal subgroups of $\mathcal{G}$. (2) A central filtration of $\mathcal{G}$ is a normal filtration $\{\mathcal{N}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$, such that $\mathcal{N}_{0}=\mathcal{G}$, $\bigcap_{p}\mathcal{N}_{p}=1$, and for every $p$ the extension of sheaves of groups $1\to\mathcal{N}_{p}/\mathcal{N}_{p+1}\to\mathcal{G}/\mathcal{N}_{p+1}\to% \mathcal{G}/\mathcal{N}_{p}\to 1$ is central. (3) Let $\{\mathcal{N}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ be a normal filtration of $\mathcal{G}$. We say that $\mathcal{G}$ is complete with respect to this filtration if the canonical homomorphism of sheaves of groups $\mathcal{G}\to\operatorname{lim}_{\leftarrow p}\,\mathcal{G}/\mathcal{N}_{p}$ is an isomorphism. (4) If $\mathcal{G}$ is complete with respect to some central filtration, then we call it a pronilpotent sheaf of groups.
Definition 3.5. (1) Let $\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ be a groupoid. A central subgroupoid of $\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ is any normal subgroupoid $\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}$ that is contained in $\operatorname{Z}(\operatorname{\mathsf{G}})$. (2) A central extension of groupoids is an extension of groupoids (3.4) such that $\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}$ is a central subgroupoid of $\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ be a groupoid. A normal subgroupoid of $\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ is a subgroupoid $\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}$ satisfying the following three conditions. (i) $\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}=\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{% \mathsf{G}}$. (ii) For every $i,j\in\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ and $g\in\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}(i,j)$ there is equality $\operatorname{Ad}(g)\bigl{(}\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}(i,i)\bigr{)}=% \operatorname{\mathsf{N}}(j,j).$ (iii) $\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}$ is totally disconnected, i.e. $\operatorname{\mathsf{N}}(i,j)=\emptyset$ for $i\neq j$.
Definition 3.10. An extension of gerbes is a diagram $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}\xrightarrow{E}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}\xrightarrow{F}% \boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}$ of morphisms in $\operatorname{\boldsymbol{\operatorname{\mathsf{PreStGr}}}}X$, such that $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ and $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}$ are gerbes, $F$ is a weak epimorphism, $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}=\operatorname{Ker}(F)$, and $E:\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}\to\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ is the inclusion.
Definition 6.5. Let $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ be a gerbe on $X$. (1) A normal filtration of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ is a descending sequence $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ of normal subgroupoids of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$. (2) A central filtration of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ is a normal filtration $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$, such that for every local object $i$ of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$, the filtration $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}_{p}(i,i)\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ of the sheaf of groups $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}(i,i)$ is central. (3) Let $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ be a normal filtration of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$. We say that $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ is complete with respect to this filtration if for every local object $i$ of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$, the sheaf $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}(i,i)$ is complete with respect to the filtration $\{\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}_{p}(i,i)\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$. (4) If $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$ is complete with respect to some central filtration, then we call it a pronilpotent gerbe.
Definition 3.21. A central extension of gerbes is an extension of gerbes $1\to\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}\xrightarrow{}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}\xrightarrow% {F}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}\to 1$ such that $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}$ is a central subgroupoid of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$.
Definition 7.2. An object $i\in\operatorname{Ob}\,\bigl{(}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}/\mathrm{Z}(\boldsymbol% {\mathcal{G}})\bigr{)}(X)$ is called a fake global object of $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{G}}$.
Definition 3.16. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a sheaf of groups on $X$. The center of $\mathcal{G}$ is the sheaf of groups $\mathrm{Z}(\mathcal{G})$ whose group of sections on an open set $U$ is $\mathrm{Z}(\mathcal{G})(U):=\{g\in\mathcal{G}(U)\mid g|_{V}\in\mathrm{Z}(% \mathcal{G}(V))\text{ for any }V\subset U\}.$
Definition 6.2. Let $\mathcal{G}$ be a sheaf of groups on $X$, with central filtration $\{\mathcal{N}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$. An open set $U\subset X$ is called acyclic with respect to $\{\mathcal{N}_{p}\}_{p\in\mathbb{N}}$ if the following two conditions hold. (i) For every $p\geq 0$ and $i>0$ the sheaf cohomology group $\mathrm{H}^{i}(U,\mathcal{N}_{p}/\mathcal{N}_{p+1})$ is trivial. (ii) For every $q\geq p\geq 0$ the canonical group homomorphism $\Gamma(U,\mathcal{N}_{p})\to\Gamma(U,\mathcal{N}_{p}/\mathcal{N}_{q})$ is surjective.
Definition 3.8. The normal subgroupoid $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{N}}$ in the proposition above is called the kernel of $F$, and it is denoted by $\operatorname{Ker}(F)$
Definition 3.2. Let $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}\to\operatorname{\mathsf{H}}$ be a morphism of groupoids. We say that $F$ is a weak epimorphism if it satisfies these conditions: (i) $F$ is essentially surjective objects. Namely for any $j\in\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{\mathsf{H}}$ there exists some $i\in\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ such that $\operatorname{\mathsf{H}}(F(i),j)\neq\emptyset$. (ii) $F$ is surjective on sets of morphisms. This means that for any $i,j\in\operatorname{Ob}\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}$ the function $F:\operatorname{\mathsf{G}}(i,j)\to\operatorname{\mathsf{H}}\bigl{(}F(i),F(j)% \bigr{)}$ is surjective.
Definition 4.15. Let $j\in\operatorname{Ob}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{H}}(X)$. If there exists a $2$-cocycle $c$ as in Construction 4.9, for some open covering $\boldsymbol{U}$, then we define the obstruction class to lifting objects to be $\operatorname{cl}^{2}_{F}(j):=[c]\in\check{\mathrm{H}}^{2}(X,\mathcal{N}).$ Otherwise we say that this obstruction class is undefined.
3.2 Definition. A quantale $Q$ is said to be a solution of triad $(L,T,R)$ if • $R$ is a $(Q,T)$-bimodule, • $L$ is a $(T,Q)$-bimodule, • there is a compatible bimorphism $R\times L\to Q,(r,l)\mapsto rl$, which means that we add further four bimorphisms (QQ, QR, LQ, RL) and require all the remaining associative laws (QQQ, LQQ, QQR, TLQ, QRT, QRL, RLQ, RTL, LQR, RLR, LRL) for scheme (* ‣ 1).
4.1 Definition. A triad $(L,T,R)$ is called central if $LR$ is a subset of the center $Z(T)$ of $T$, i.e. $lrt=tlr$ for every $l\in L,t\in T,r\in R$.
3.6 Definition. Let $C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi}}{{\to}}Q$ be a couple. A quantale $K$ together with quantale morphisms $\phi_{0}:C\to K,\phi_{1}:K\to Q$ such that $\phi_{1}\phi_{0}=\phi$ is called a couple factorization if the $K$-bimodule structure on $C$ obtained by restricting scalars along $\phi_{1}$ makes $\phi_{0}$ a coupling map. Namely, it holds that $\displaystyle\phi_{0}(\phi_{1}(k)c)$ $\displaystyle=k\phi_{0}(c),$ $\displaystyle\phi_{0}(c\phi_{1}(k))$ $\displaystyle=\phi_{0}(c)k$ for all $c\in C,k\in K$.
3.8 Definition. A triad $(L,T,R)$ is called strong if $l\leq(l1_{R})1_{L}$ and $r\leq 1_{R}(1_{L}r)$ for every $l\in L,r\in R$, unital if $T$ is a unital quantale and $L,R$ are unital $T$-modules, and strict if it is strong, unital, and $1_{L}1_{R}=e_{T}$.
3.1 Definition. A (quantum) triad consists of the following data: • quantale $T$, • right $T$-module $R$, • left $T$-module $L$, • and bimorphism $L\times R\to T$ compatible with the module actions, i.e., there are four bimorphisms, referred as (TT, RT, TL, LR), satisfying all the five reasonable associative laws (TTT, TTL, RTT, LRT, TLR).
4.3 Definition. An triad $(L,T,R)$ is called involutive if $T$ is involutive and there is an isomorphism $L\stackrel{{\scriptstyle*}}{{\cong}}R$ such that $\displaystyle(tl)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=l^{*}t^{*},$ $\displaystyle(rt)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=t^{*}r^{*},$ $\displaystyle(lr)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=r^{*}l^{*}$ for all $r\in R,l\in L,t\in T$. A solution $Q$ of involutive triad $(L,T,R)$ is called involutive if $Q$ is an involutive quantale and $\displaystyle(qr)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=r^{*}q^{*},$ $\displaystyle(lq)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=q^{*}l^{*},$ $\displaystyle(rl)^{*}$ $\displaystyle=l^{*}r^{*}$ for all $q\in Q,r\in R,l\in L$. A couple $C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi}}{{\to}}Q$ is said to be involutive if $\phi$ is an involutive morphism of involutive quantales and $(qc)^{*}=c^{*}q^{*}$ for every $q\in Q,c\in C$. A couple factorization $C\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi_{0}}}{{\to}}K\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi_{1}}}{{% \to}}Q$ is called involutive if $K$ is an involutive quantale and $\phi_{0},\phi_{1}$ are involutive morphisms.
Definition 6.3. A right $C$-comodule $M$ is called chain (or uniserial) if the lattice of its right subcomodules is a chain. A coalgebra $C$ is called right serial if its indecomposable injective right comodules are uniserial, equivalently, $C$ is a direct sum of uniserial right comodules. $C$ is called serial if it is both left and right serial.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ be two finitely accessible categories. We call $\mathcal{C}$ and $\mathcal{D}$ symmetric categories if there is a duality between the categories $\mathcal{B}({\rm fp}(\mathcal{C}))$ and $\mathcal{B}({\rm fp}(\mathcal{D}))$.
Definition 4.1. A class $\mathcal{C}$ of morphisms of a category $\mathcal{K}$ is called cone-coreflective if, for each morphism $f$ in $\mathcal{K}$, the comma-category $\mathcal{C}\downarrow f$ has a weakly terminal set.
Definition 2.7. A functor $F:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{L}$ is called class-$\lambda$-accessible (where $\lambda$ is a regular cardinal) if $\mathcal{K}$ and $\mathcal{L}$ are class-$\lambda$-accessible categories and $F$ preserves $\lambda$-filtered colimits. A class-$\lambda$-accessible functor preserving $\lambda$-presentable objects is called strongly class-$\lambda$-accessible. $F$ is called (strongly) class-accessible if it is (strongly) class-$\lambda$-accessible for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 4.7. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a class-locally $\lambda$-presentable category. A weak factorization system $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ in $\mathcal{K}$ is called cofibrantly class-$\lambda$-generated if $\mathcal{L}=\operatorname{cof}(\mathcal{C})$ for a cone-coreflective class $\mathcal{C}$ of morphisms such that (1) morphisms from $\mathcal{C}$ are $\lambda$-presentable and (2) any morphism between $\lambda$-presentable objects has a weak factorization with the middle object $\lambda$-presentable. A cone-coreflective class $\mathcal{C}$ of morphisms will be called $\lambda$-bounded if $(\operatorname{cof}(\mathcal{C}),\operatorname{cof}(\mathcal{C})^{\square})$ satisfies conditions (1) and (2) above. We say that $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ is cofibrantly class-generated if there is a regular cardinal $\lambda$ such that $(\mathcal{L},\mathcal{R})$ is cofibrantly class-$\lambda$-generated. The same for bounded.
Definition 2.1. A category $\mathcal{K}$ is called class-$\lambda$-accessible, where $\lambda$ is a regular cardinal, provided that (1) $\mathcal{K}$ has $\lambda$-filtered colimits, (2) $\mathcal{K}$ has a class $\mathcal{A}$ of $\lambda$-presentable objects such that every object of $\mathcal{K}$ is a $\lambda$-filtered colimit of objects from $\mathcal{A}$. A category is class-accessible if it is class-$\lambda$-accessible for some regular cardinal $\lambda$. A complete and cocomplete class-$\lambda$-accessible category is called class-locally $\lambda$-presentable. A category is class-locally presentable if it is class-locally $\lambda$-presentable for some regular cardinal $\lambda$. Finally, a category $\mathcal{K}$ is called class-preaccessible if it satisfies (2) for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 11. [ASS] Let $\mathcal{C}$ be Krull-Schmidt. A torsion theory $(\mathscr{T},\mathscr{F})$ in $\mathrm{mod}(\mathcal{C})$ splits, if every indecomposable $M\in\mathrm{mod}(\mathcal{C})$ is, either in $\mathscr{T}$ or in $\mathscr{F}$.
Definition 14. [ARS] Let $I$ be the integers in one of the intervals $(-\infty,n]$, $[n,\infty)$, $[m,n]$ for $m<n$ or $\{1,\ldots,n\}$ modulo $n$. Let $\cdots\rightarrow X_{i}\xrightarrow{f_{i}}X_{i+1}\rightarrow\cdots$ be a path in the Auslander-Reiten quiver $(\Gamma,\tau)$ with each index in $I$. This path is said to be sectional if $\tau X_{i+2}\ncong X_{i}$.
Definition 9. Given a skeletally small pre additive category $\mathcal{C}$, we introduce the following notion of tensor product: given an abelian group $G$ and an object $M$ in $\mathrm{Mod}(\mathcal{C})$ the tensor product $G\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}M$, is the functor defined in objects as $(G\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}M)(C)=G\otimes_{\mathbb{Z}}M(C)$.
Definition 15. The set of predeccessors of $\Sigma$ (successors, $succ\Sigma$), $pre\Sigma$, is the set of indecomposables $X$ such that there is a $T\in\Sigma_{0}$ and an integer $n>0$ with $T=\tau^{-n}X$ ($T=\tau^{n}X$).
Definition 10. Let $\mathcal{C}$ a skeletally small pre additive category $\mathcal{C}$ and let $\mathcal{T}$ be a tilting subcategory of $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})$. Let’s denote by $|\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})|$ the set of isomorphism classes of objects in $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})$. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be the free abelian group generated by $|\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})|$ and $\mathcal{R}$ the subgroup of $\mathcal{A}$ generated by relations $M-K-L$ such that $0\rightarrow K\rightarrow M\rightarrow L\rightarrow 0$ is a short exact sequence in $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})$. Then, the Groethendiek group of $\mathcal{C}$ is $K_{0}(\mathcal{C})=\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{R}$.
Definition 12. A full subcategory $\mathcal{T}$ of $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(C)$ is a partial tilting, if its objects satisfy the following two conditions: (i) For each object $T$ in $\mathcal{T}$ there is an exact sequence $0\rightarrow P_{1}\rightarrow P_{0}\rightarrow T\rightarrow 0$, with $P_{i}$ finitely generated projective. (ii) For every pair of objects $T_{i}$ and $T_{j}$ in $\mathcal{T}$, $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(T_{i},T_{j})=0$.
Definition 7. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be an arbitray category and $\mathbf{X}\rightarrow Y=\{X_{i}\xrightarrow{f_{i}}Y\}_{i\in I}$ a family of morphisms. A fibered product of $\mathbf{X}\rightarrow Y$ is a pair $(\{P\xrightarrow{p_{i}}X_{i}\}_{i\in I},L)$, where $L:P\rightarrow Y$ is a morphism such that $f_{i}p_{i}=L$, and satisfies the following universal property: If $(\{Q\xrightarrow{q_{i}}X_{i}\}_{i\in I},L^{\prime})$ is a pair such that for each $i\in I$, $f_{i}q_{i}=L^{\prime}$, then there exists a unique morphism $\eta:Q\rightarrow P$, such that $L\eta=L^{\prime}$, and for each $i\in I$, $p_{i}\eta=q_{i}$.
Definition 4. An additive category $\mathcal{C}$ is Krull-Schmidt, if every object in $\mathcal{C}$ decomposes in a finite sum of objects whose endomorphism ring is local.
Definition 1. [AQM] Given a preadditive skeletally small category $\mathcal{C}$, we say $\mathcal{C}$ has pseudokernels, if given a map $f:C_{1}\rightarrow C_{0}$ there exists a map $g:C_{2}\rightarrow C_{1}$ such that the sequence: $\mathcal{C}(\;C_{2})\overset{(\;,g)}{\rightarrow}\mathcal{C}(\;C_{1})\overset{% (\;,f)}{\rightarrow}\mathcal{C}(\;,C_{0})$ is exact.
Definition 6. By an ideal of the additive category $\mathcal{C}$ we understand a sub bifunctor of $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(\;,\;).$
Definition 3. An $\mathrm{Hom}$-finite $R$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is dualizing, if the functor $D:(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{mod}(R))\rightarrow(\mathcal{C},\mathrm{mod}(R))$ induces a duality between the categories $\mathrm{mod}(\mathcal{C})$ and $\mathrm{mod}(\mathcal{C}^{op}).$
Definition 5. The Jacobson radical of $\mathcal{C}$, $\mathrm{rad}_{\mathcal{C}}(\;,\;)$, is a subbifunctor of $\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(\;,\;)$ defined in objects as: $\mathrm{rad}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)=\{f\in\mathrm{Hom}_{\mathcal{C}}(X,Y)\mid$for any map $g:Y\rightarrow X$, $1-gf$ is invertible }. If $M$ is a $\mathcal{C}$-module , then we denote by $\mathrm{rad}M$ the intersection of all maximal subfunctors of $M$.
Definition 2. Let $R$ be a commutative artin ring, an $R$-category $\mathcal{C}$, is a pre additive category such that $\mathcal{C}(C_{1},C_{2})$ is an $R$-module and composition is $R$-bilinear. Under these conditions $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})$ is a $R$-category which we identify with the category of functors $(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{Mod}(R))$. An $R$-category $\mathcal{C}$ is $\mathrm{Hom}$-finite, if for each pair of objects $C_{1},C_{2}$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the $R$-module $\mathcal{C}(C_{1},C_{2})$ is finitely generated. We denote by $(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{mod}(R))$, the full subcategory of $(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(R))$ consisting of the $\mathcal{C}$-modules such that; for every $C$ in $\mathcal{C}$ the $R$-module $M(C)$ is finitely generated. The category $(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{mod}(R))$ is abelian and the inclusion $(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{mod}(R))\rightarrow(\mathcal{C}^{op},\mathrm{\mathrm% {Mod}}(R))$ is exact.
Definition 13. [ASS] Let $(\Gamma,\tau)$ be a connected translation quiver. A connected full subquiver $\Sigma$ is a section of $\Gamma$ if the following conditions are satisfied: (S1) If $X_{0}\rightarrow X_{1}\rightarrow\cdots\rightarrow X_{t}$ is a path in $\Sigma$ of lenght $l\geq 1$, then $X_{0}\neq X_{t}$. (S2) For each $X\in\Gamma_{0}$, there exist a unique $n\in\mathbb{Z}$ such that $\tau^{n}X\in\Sigma_{0}$. (S3) If $X_{0}\rightarrow X_{1}\rightarrow\cdots\rightarrow X_{t}$ is a path in $\Gamma$ with $X_{0},X_{t}\in\Sigma$, then $X_{i}\in\Sigma_{0}$ for all $i$ such that $0\leq i\leq t$.
Definition 8. Let $\mathcal{C}$ an annuli variety, a subcategory $\mathcal{T}$ of $\mathrm{\mathrm{Mod}}(\mathcal{C})$ is a tilting category, if every object in $\mathcal{T}$ is finitely presented and the following conditions are satisfied: (i) $\mathrm{pdim}\mathcal{T}\leq 1.$ (ii) We have $\mathrm{Ext}_{\mathcal{C}}^{1}(T_{i},T_{j})=0$, for every pair of objects $T_{i},T_{j}$ in $\mathcal{T}$. (iii) For every object $C$ in $\mathcal{C}$, the representable functor $\mathcal{C}(\;\;,C)$ has a resolution $0\rightarrow\mathcal{C}(\;\;,C)\rightarrow T_{1}\rightarrow T_{2}\rightarrow 0% \text{,}$ with $T_{1},T_{2}$ in $\mathcal{T}$.
Definition 5.1. A morphism $\alpha\colon X\to Y$ in a category ${\mathsf{C}}$ is said to be right determined by a class ${\mathsf{D}}$ of objects of ${\mathsf{C}}$ if for every morphism $\alpha^{\prime}\colon X^{\prime}\to Y$ the following conditions are equivalent: (1) The morphism $\alpha^{\prime}$ factors through $\alpha$. (2) For every morphism $\phi\colon C\to X^{\prime}$ with $C\in{\mathsf{D}}$ the composite $\alpha^{\prime}\phi$ factors through $\alpha$.
Definition 3.1 (Auslander–Reiten [3]). A $k$-linear additive Hom-finite essentially small and idempotent complete category ${\mathsf{C}}$ is called dualising $k$-variety if the assignment $F\mapsto DF$ induces an equivalence $(\operatorname{\mathsf{mod}}\nolimits{\mathsf{C}})^{\mathrm{op}}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\sim}}{{\longrightarrow}}\operatorname{\mathsf{mod}}\nolimits({% \mathsf{C}}^{\mathrm{op}}).$
Definition 2.1 (Auslander [1]). A morphism $\alpha\colon X\to Y$ in some fixed category is said to be right determined by an object $C$ if for every morphism $\alpha^{\prime}\colon X^{\prime}\to Y$ the following conditions are equivalent: (1) The morphism $\alpha^{\prime}$ factors through $\alpha$. (2) For every morphism $\phi\colon C\to X^{\prime}$ the composite $\alpha^{\prime}\phi$ factors through $\alpha$. A morphism is left determined by $C$ if it is right determined by $C$ when viewed as morphism in the opposite category.
Definition 2.6. An additive category ${\mathsf{C}}$ is said to have right determined morphisms if for every object $Y\in{\mathsf{C}}$ the following holds: (1) Given an object $C\in{\mathsf{C}}$ and an $\operatorname{End}\nolimits_{\mathsf{C}}(C)$-submodule $H\subseteq\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{\mathsf{C}}(C,Y)$, there is a right $C$-determined morphism $\alpha\colon X\to Y$ with $\operatorname{Im}\nolimits\operatorname{Hom}\nolimits_{\mathsf{C}}(C,\alpha)=H$. (2) Every morphism ending in $Y$ is right determined by an object in ${\mathsf{C}}$.
Definition 2.7. Let $\mathcal{A}$ be a complete simplicial category and $f:A\to B$ be a morphism in $\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{A})$. The Serre construction on $f$ is the object $S(f)$ of $\mathcal{P}(\mathcal{A})$ defined as a pullback $\xymatrix{S(f)\ar[r]^{r}\ar[d]_{q}&B^{\Delta_{1}}\ar[d]^{B^{j}}\\ B\ar[r]_{f}&B}$ where $j:\Delta_{0}\to\Delta_{1}$ sends $0$ to $0$.
Definition 3.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a class-combinatorial simplicial model category and $\cal F$ a class of morphisms of $\mathcal{K}$. Assume that $\cal F$ contains only cofibrations between cofibrant objects. An object $K$ in $\mathcal{K}$ is called $\cal F$-local if it is fibrant and $\hom(f,K)\colon\hom(B,K)\to\hom(A,K)$ is a weak equivalence of simplicial sets for each $f\colon A\to B$ in $\mathcal{F}$. A morphism $h$ of $\mathcal{K}$ is called an $\mathcal{F}$-local equivalence if $\hom(\tilde{h},K)$ is a weak equivalence for each $\mathcal{F}$-local object $K$; here, $\tilde{h}$ is a cofibrant approximation of $h$. The full subcategory of $\mathcal{K}$ consisting of $\mathcal{F}$-local objects is denoted $\operatorname{Loc}(\mathcal{F})$ and the full subcategory of $\mathcal{K}^{\to}$ consisting of $\mathcal{F}$-local equivalences is denoted $\operatorname{LEq}(\mathcal{F})$. We say that there exists a left Bousfield localization of $\mathcal{F}$ if cofibrations in $\mathcal{K}$ and $\mathcal{F}$-local equivalences form a model category structure on $\mathcal{K}$.
Definition 3.13. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a model category equipped with a homotopy idempotent functor $L:\mathcal{K}\to\mathcal{K}$ preserving weak equivalences. A left Bousfield localization of $\mathcal{K}$ with respect to $L$, or just $L$-localization of $\mathcal{K}$ is a new model structure on $\mathcal{K}$ such that the class of cofibrations coincides with the original class of cofibrations in $\mathcal{K}$ and the class of weak equivalences is $\operatorname{LEq}(L)$. New fibrations are called $L$-fibrations.
Definition 2.11. A class-combinatorial model category $\mathcal{K}$ is nice if the class of weak equivalences $\mathcal{W}$ is a class-accessible, strongly class-accessibly embedded subcategory of $\mathcal{K}^{\to}$.
Definition 2.1. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a class locally-$\lambda$-presentable model category. We say that $\mathcal{K}$ is class-$\lambda$-combinatorial if both (cofibrations, trivial fibrations) and (trivial cofibrations, fibrations) are cofibrantly class-$\mu$-generated weak factorization systems for every regular cardinal $\mu\trianglerighteq\lambda$. It is called class-combinatorial if it is class-$\lambda$-combinatorial for some regular cardinal $\lambda$.
Definition 3.4. Let $\mathcal{K}$ be a simplicial model category and $f:A\to B$ a cofibration of cofibrant objects. Consider a pushout $\xymatrix@=4pc{\partial\Delta_{n}\otimes A\ar[r]^{\operatorname{id}\otimes f}% \ar[d]_{i_{n}\otimes\operatorname{id}}&\partial\Delta_{n}\otimes B\ar[d]^{p_{n% 1}}\\ \Delta_{n}\otimes A\ar[r]_{p_{n2}}&P_{f,n}}$ where $i_{n}:\partial\Delta_{n}\to\Delta_{n}$ is the inclusion of the boundary into a simplex. Let $h_{f,n}:P_{f,n}\to\Delta_{n}\otimes B$ be the canonical morphism, which is a cofibration since $\mathcal{K}$ is simplicial. Cofibrations $h_{f,n}$, $n=0,1,\dots$ are called $f$-horns. If $\mathcal{F}$ is a class of cofibrations, then we denote by $\operatorname{\textup{Hor}}(\mathcal{F})$ the collection of all $f$-horns, for all $f\in\mathcal{F}$.
